.TH _PRINTF 3 "April 2026" "Holberton School" "Library Functions Manual"
.SH NAME
_printf \- custom implementation of the printf function
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include "main.h"
.PP
.BI "int _printf(const char *" "format" ", ...);"
.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B _printf
function produces output according to a format string and writes
it to stdout, the standard output stream.
.PP
The format string is composed of zero or more directives.
Each directive is either a regular character, which is copied
unchanged to the output, or a conversion specifier.
.PP
.B Conversion Specifiers:
.TP
.B %c
Prints a single character.
.TP
.B %s
Prints a string of characters. If the string is NULL,
prints (null).
.TP
.B %d
Prints a decimal integer.
.TP
.B %i
Prints an integer.
.TP
.B %%
Prints a literal percent sign.
.SH RETURN VALUE
Returns the number of characters printed, excluding the null byte.
Returns \-1 if the format string is NULL or if % is at end of string.
.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
.B _printf("Hello %s\\n", "Shahd");
.PP
Output: Hello Shahd
.PP
.B _printf("Number: %d\\n", 42);
.PP
Output: Number: 42
.PP
.B _printf("Percent: %%\\n");
.PP
Output: Percent: %
